LEVEL 5 — THE FALLEN DISTRICT (Late-Game Ground Level)
================================================================================
Theme: A section of the city that fell long ago and crashed into the land far
below the clouds. Nature has reclaimed it. Buildings are overgrown ruins.
The ground is a mix of old city stone and wild new growth. It's eerie — a
glimpse of what happens when pieces fall. Life goes on, but differently.

PROMPT:
Tileset restyle edit, the green grass area should be changed to dark, lush,
overgrown jungle-like vegetation — deep emerald greens and dark teals. The
grass should look thick, wild, and untamed, much more aggressive than Level 1.
Weave in small bioluminescent dots (tiny glowing spores or fungi) among the
grass blades. The edge should have roots and creeping vines spilling over,
showing that nature is aggressively consuming everything.

The brown dirt area should be changed to a mix of crumbled city stone and dark
rich soil. Replace the wavy zigzag texture with a layered texture showing
broken brick and masonry fragments embedded in dark earth — you can see old
tile patterns, bits of carved stone, and corroded metal in the cross-section.
Occasional faintly glowing crystal veins should still be visible, but dimmer
and more overgrown than in other levels — the crystal energy is fading here.

The decorative grass blades should be restyled as wild jungle plants — large
fern fronds, thick moss clumps, and tall mushrooms with bioluminescent caps
(soft green and blue glow). Mix in a couple of small ruined artifacts poking
out of the undergrowth — a broken gear, a fragment of carved stone, the corner
of an old sign — hints of the civilization that fell.

The hanging vines should be restyled as thick, heavy tropical vines with large
leaves — the kind that have been growing for decades undisturbed. Some should
have bioluminescent flowers or pods hanging from them. The vines should look
weighty and ancient, draped in moss, very different from the delicate ivy of
Level 1.

The gem collectibles should look partially overgrown — crystal shards with
small vines curling around them and moss starting to creep across their
surfaces. But the inner glow still pulses through, refusing to be buried.
This visual tells the story: the crystals endure even when everything else
is reclaimed by nature.

Overall it should have a retro handheld gaming style with an overgrown
post-ruins vibe — think the Forgotten Crossroads overtaken by jungle in
Hollow Knight, or Ivy's garden level in Batman TAS. Dark, saturated greens
and teals with warm bioluminescent accents. The feeling is ancient, wild,
and slightly ominous.


