BONUS IDEAS — ADDITIONAL LEVEL CONCEPTS (Less Detailed, For Future Development)
================================================================================

LEVEL IDEA: THE ARCHIVE
- Old library/knowledge district that fell. Platforms are giant book stacks,
  stone shelves, and scroll cases. The "grass" becomes dusty paper and aged
  parchment curling over edges. The "dirt" becomes stacked books and dark
  wood shelving. Crystal energy preserves some texts, making them glow.
  Cozy but abandoned. Think the Great Library at Alexandria if it floated
  and then crashed. Warm amber and dusty brown palette with crystal blue
  accents.

LEVEL IDEA: THE WATERWORKS
- The old aqueduct and water system of the floating city. Platforms are stone
  pipes, reservoirs, and water channels. The "grass" becomes flowing water
  surfaces or wet moss on pipe surfaces. The "dirt" becomes old stone pipe
  interiors and weathered copper/bronze infrastructure. Water still flows in
  some sections, powered by crystal energy — but in broken sections it pours
  into the void. Teal, dark stone grey, and copper-green patina palette.

LEVEL IDEA: THE NIGHT MARKET
- A district where people once traded and celebrated. Platforms are old market
  stalls, awnings, and cobblestone streets. The "grass" becomes tattered colorful
  fabric awning tops. The "dirt" becomes layered market stall wood and old
  cobblestone. Torn paper lanterns and faded banners serve as decorative elements.
  Crystal energy keeps a few lanterns still flickering. Warm but melancholy —
  a party that ended long ago. Faded warm colors with soft crystal glow accents.

LEVEL IDEA: THE FORGE
- The old industrial district where crystal-powered machines were built. Platforms
  are metal grating, anvil surfaces, and cooled magma channels. The "grass"
  becomes glowing hot metal or cooling slag with ember particles. The "dirt"
  becomes dark iron and industrial stone. Machinery parts and gears serve as
  decorative elements. Some forges still burn with crystal energy. Dark iron
  grey, ember orange, and searing crystal-blue palette. Hot and heavy atmosphere.


================================================================================
IDEAS FOR CHANGING THE GRASS AND ROCK TILESET
================================================================================

When the grass and rock tileset becomes available, here are themes that would
work well with rock as the primary material instead of dirt/earth:

1. MOUNTAIN PASS variant — Grey-blue mountain stone with alpine grass and small
   tough flowers on top. Snow dusting on some surfaces. Crystal veins visible
   in cliff faces. Feels high-altitude and windswept.

2. ANCIENT RUINS variant — Carved stone blocks with geometric patterns (the old
   city's architecture). Moss and wild grass growing in the cracks. Some carvings
   still glow with residual crystal energy. Feels archaeological and mysterious.

3. VOLCANIC RIFT variant — Dark basalt rock with glowing magma cracks. The
   "grass" becomes heat-resistant crystal formations or fire-moss. Used for
   levels near the underside of the floating city where the crystal energy
   generates extreme heat. Feels dangerous and primordial.

4. FROZEN SPIRE variant — Ice-covered pale blue-white rock with frost crystals
   instead of grass. The crystal energy has gone cold in this district, freezing
   everything. Icicle formations instead of vines. Feels desolate, crystalline,
   and hauntingly beautiful.

5. VOID-TOUCHED variant — Corrupted dark purple-black rock with reality-warping
   distortions. The "grass" becomes strange void-growths — organic but wrong,
   shifting colors. This is for areas where the Void has started creeping UP
   into the fallen pieces. Feels alien and threatening. The crystals here sing
   a discordant, uncomfortable song.


================================================================================
GENERAL STYLE NOTES
================================================================================

- Consistent pixel art resolution across all tilesets (match the reference).
- Every level should have crystal veins/elements present somewhere — they are
  the connective visual thread across the entire game.
- The collectible gems should always be recognizable but themed to each level.
- The Heart Crystal fragment (rose-pink) should always stand out as the most
  important collectible regardless of the level palette.
- Consider having a subtle visual progression: crystals get more prominent and
  active as the player gets closer to the Heart Chamber. Early levels have
  faint, hidden veins. Late levels have intense, pulsing crystal everywhere.
- The retro handheld gaming style should be consistent — think GBA/DS era pixel
  art. Clean pixels, readable silhouettes, but with modern color depth and
  lighting effects (glows, subtle gradients within the pixel art).
- Each level's palette should be distinct enough that a player immediately knows
  where they are just from the colors, even without other context.
